170–1213","1170–1234":"1170–1234","1187–1234":"1187–1234","1137–1211":"1137–1211","1135–Female":"1135–Deceased","before 1168":"1168","1187":"1187","1143":"1143","1241":"1241","1151":"1151","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1137":"1137","1214":"1214","1213":"1213","1168":"1168","1135":"1135","1234":"1234","1178":"1178","1211":"1211","1189":"1189","Menteith, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Menteith, Rusky, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gilchrist","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (western) and Irish (Down): from Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Chríosd</i>, <i>Mac Gille Chríosd</i> ‘son of the servant of Christ’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kilcrease","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Gilchrist  .","History: Robert Kilcrease (<i>c.</i> 1750–1808) came from Scotland(probably Kilmarnock) to Edgefield, SC, <i>c.</i> 1770."]},{"name":"Gilchrest","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Gilchrist  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Gilkerson","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Chrìosd</i> ‘son of <i>Gille Chrìosd</i>' (see   Gilchrist  )."]},{"name":"Gilkey","meanings":["Irish (northern): possibly a pet form of the Scottishpersonal name   Gilchrist  ."]},{"name":"Gilcrest","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Gilchrist  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Gilcrease","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Gilchrist  ."]}]},{"name":"Agatha","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Agnes   and   Agatha ."],"variants":[{"name":"Agnes","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agatha Gilchrist was born in 1151, in Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Robert Mac Eruni Gilchrist, was 14 and her mother, Elizabeth of Menteith, was 16. She married Gilchrist Menteith - First Earl of Menteith in 1168, in Perthshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1178, in her hometown, at the age of 27."},"et":{"1151–1178":"1151–1178","1143–1214":"1143–1214","1150–1189":"1150–1189","1168–1241":"1168–1241","1170–1213":"1170–1213","1170–1234":"1170–1234","1187–1234":"1187–1234","1137–1211":"1137–1211","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","before 1168":"1168","1187":"1187","1143":"1143","1241":"1241","1151":"1151","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1137":"1137","1214":"1214","1213":"1213","1168":"1168","1135":"1135","1234":"1234","1178":"1178","1211":"1211","1189":"1189","Menteith, Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Perthshire, Scotland":"Perthshire, Scotland","Menteith, Rusky, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1151–1178":"1151–1178","1143–1214":"1143–1214","1150–1189":"1150–1189","1168–1241":"1168–1241","1170–1213":"1170–1213","1170–1234":"1170–1234","1187–1234":"1187–1234","1137–1211":"1137–1211","1135–Female":"1135–Kuollut","be